The [Total Cost Curve][] is the mirror image of the [Total Product Curve][] because this the slope of the curve is driven by the Marginal Product Labor, in the [Total Cost Curve] this slope is called the [Marginal Cost of Production][]. The **marginal cost** is the **increase** in *total cost* that arises from an **extra unit of production**. $$MC = \Delta TC / \Delta Q$$

Other related concepts are:

  * **average total cost** which is the *total cost* divided by the quantity of output. Shows the cost of the typical unit, but it does not show how much total cost will change as the level of production is increased. $$ATC = TC / Q$$

  * **average fixed cost** which is the *fixed cost* divided by the quantity of output. $$AFC = FC / Q$$

  * **average variable cost** which is the *variable cost* divided by the quantity of output. $$AVC = VC / Q$$


